BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Academic,Lecture / Presentation / Talk,Performance
DESCRIPTION:Musician\, scholar\, and storyteller Dr. Julian Saporiti invite
 s audiences to experience the Pacific Northwest’s landscapes through an art
 istic lens that weaves together music\, history\, and ecology. Drawing on h
 is work as musician-in-residence at Portland’s Hoyt Arboretum\, Saporiti us
 es field recordings\, images\, and song to explore how the natural world su
 stains our spiritual and intellectual lives\, offering a vision of sustaina
 bility that unites ecology with imagination. Known for his acclaimed No-No 
 Boy Project—praised by NPR as “one of the most insurgent pieces of music yo
 u’ll ever hear”—Saporiti bridges scholarship and performance\, creating a s
 pace where environmental awareness and storytelling converge in sound.\n\nD
 oors open at 6:30 pm for a light desserts reception. For more information a
 nd ADA accommodations please contact garaventa@up.edu or 503-943-7702. Free
  and open to all.
DTEND:20260218T041500Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160901Z
DTSTART:20260218T030000Z
GEO:45.57252;-122.724823
LOCATION:Dundon-Berchtold Hall\, Brian Doyle Auditorium (DB004)
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Field Notes in Sound with Julian Saporiti
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51587349175005
URL:https://up.enterprise.localist.com/event/field-notes-in-sound-with-juli
 an-saporiti
END:VEVENT
